MIDTERM : Analytics Technology¶

In this assignment you are going to have several tasks:

  1. Import several CSV files:

    • Physicians
    • Scripts (files 1 – 10)
    • Zip Codes

  2. Create provider summary and org summary tables

  3. There are 10 analysis questions each requiring a TABLE and at least 1 CHART (Barplot) To get the results you’ll likely need to break things up into steps and perform various steps including:

    • Query to filter data
    • Merge to join data
    • N-largest / N-smallest (top N, Bottom N)
    • Concat to append datasets together
    • agg (sum, count, mean, min, max)
    • create barplots using seaborn
    • Rename columns using df.column = [“col1”,”col2”,…]

  4. Devise 5 of your own analysis questions answered with tables and visualizations

  5. Extra Credit

RES09 Analysis:¶

The graphs about show the hydrocodone and oxycodone prescriptions to Medicare patients in our cities of interest. We can observe that Knoxville, TN has the highest total day supply, indicating higher use of these opioids. TN has a high total sum in general which could be because of state laws and demographics. However, when we take the mean of the total day supply, Knoxville is replaced by Spartunburg as the city with the highest mean of total day supply. This is interesting because it shows that the mean is likely affected by outlier bias and doesn't necessarily give a holistic picture of the day supply of the opiods.

For a better analysis, information like demographics, patient age groups, and other prescription drug data can be studied. State laws could also be helpful

RES10 ANALYSIS¶

The graph shows the day supply of Hydrocodone and Oxycodone (the most most popular opiods) per person. We see that Spartanbug and Florence have a really high daily supply per person which is cause for concern. It could suggest misuse of opiods in the state of South Carolina. To further this analysis, it could be helpful to research the demographics, income, and health status of the people living in those cities. Comparing these results to national and state averages would paint a more holistic picture of the issue
